description:
Final pass: This was missed because reviewers focused on whether the loop was infinite, not its interaction with hardware watchdogs.

Root cause: At lines 201-206:
  while (1) {
      led_set(1);
      k_sleep(K_MSEC(200));
      led_set(0);
      k_sleep(K_MSEC(200));
  }

This infinite loop blinks the LED to indicate fatal LoRa failure. However:
1. Many embedded systems have hardware watchdogs (enabled via CONFIG_WATCHDOG)
2. The Zephyr idle thread typically kicks the watchdog
3. k_sleep yields to other threads, so the idle thread can run

But if CONFIG_WDT_DISABLE_AT_BOOT is false and the watchdog timeout is short (e.g., 500ms), and this is the only running application thread, the system may reset unexpectedly.

Actually, k_sleep allows other threads (including the idle thread) to run, so the watchdog should be kicked. The issue only arises if:
1. Watchdog is not kicked by idle thread (custom configuration)
2. Watchdog timeout is less than 400ms (two LED cycles)
3. No other threads are running

This is a configuration-dependent edge case, not a code bug. But worth documenting.

Impact: On systems with aggressive watchdog configuration, the 'fatal error' LED pattern may be interrupted by watchdog reset.

Fix: Either feed the watchdog explicitly in the loop, or document the assumption that default Zephyr watchdog handling is active.
